Files:
- platform/plugin-sdk/src/fetch.ts (fix postFormData)
- platform/plugin-sdk/src/fetch.test.ts (add test)

Context:
postFormData is a convenience wrapper for POST requests with FormData body. When the body is FormData, the browser MUST auto-set Content-Type to `multipart/form-data; boundary=<generated>`. If any explicit Content-Type header is set, the browser uses it verbatim WITHOUT the boundary, causing the server to fail to parse the multipart body.

Current code (platform/plugin-sdk/src/fetch.ts lines 313-330):
```typescript
export const postFormData: PostFormData = (async (
  url: string,
  body: FormData,
  init?: FetchFromPageOptions,
  schema?: z.ZodType,
): Promise<unknown> => {
  const extraHeaders = init?.headers ? Object.fromEntries(new Headers(init.headers).entries()) : {};
  return fetchJSONImpl(
    url,
    {
      ...init,
      method: 'POST',
      headers: { ...extraHeaders },
      body,
    },
    schema,
  );
}) as PostFormData;
```

The `extraHeaders` object is built from ALL user-provided headers including Content-Type. The fix is to delete `content-type` from `extraHeaders` before spreading it. Note: `new Headers()` lowercases header names, so the key to delete is `'content-type'` (lowercase).

Changes:
After `const extraHeaders = ...;`, add: `delete extraHeaders['content-type'];`

For the test, use the existing `/echo-headers` test endpoint which returns `{ contentType, hasCookies }`. Add a test like:
```typescript
test('strips user-provided Content-Type header to preserve multipart boundary', async () => {
  const formData = new FormData();
  formData.append('field', 'value');
  const data = await postFormData<{ contentType: string; hasCookies: boolean }>(
    `${baseUrl}/echo-headers`,
    formData,
    { headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' } },
  );
  expect(data?.contentType).toMatch(/^multipart\/form-data/);
});
```

Constraints:
- Do NOT change any other fetch utility (postJSON, putJSON, patchJSON, etc.) — those correctly allow Content-Type override because their body encoding doesn't depend on the Content-Type header.
- Do NOT change the FetchFromPageOptions type or PostFormData interface.

Files:
- platform/plugin-sdk/src/storage.ts (fix setLocalStorage and removeLocalStorage)
- platform/plugin-sdk/src/storage.test.ts (add tests)

Context:
getLocalStorage (lines 16-54) has an iframe fallback pattern: when `window.localStorage` is undefined (Discord deletes the property), it creates a hidden same-origin iframe, accesses `iframe.contentWindow.localStorage`, reads the value, then removes the iframe in a finally block. This works because same-origin iframes retain access to the underlying storage even when the main frame's property has been deleted.

setLocalStorage (lines 109-116) and removeLocalStorage (lines 148-155) do NOT have this fallback. They use `const storage = window.localStorage as Storage | undefined; storage?.setItem(key, value);` which is a silent no-op when storage is undefined. No warning is logged.

Current setLocalStorage:
```typescript
export const setLocalStorage = (key: string, value: string): void => {
  try {
    const storage = window.localStorage as Storage | undefined;
    storage?.setItem(key, value);
  } catch (error) {
    log.warn(`setLocalStorage failed for key "${key}"`, error);
  }
};
```

Current removeLocalStorage:
```typescript
export const removeLocalStorage = (key: string): void => {
  try {
    const storage = window.localStorage as Storage | undefined;
    storage?.removeItem(key);
  } catch (error) {
    log.warn(`removeLocalStorage failed for key "${key}"`, error);
  }
};
```

Changes:
Refactor the iframe fallback into a shared helper (to avoid tripling the same code), then use it in getLocalStorage, setLocalStorage, removeLocalStorage, and findLocalStorageEntry. The helper creates a hidden iframe, gets its localStorage, runs a callback with the storage, then removes the iframe in a finally block.

Suggested helper:
```typescript
const withIframeStorage = <T>(fn: (storage: Storage) => T, fallback: T): T => {
  try {
    const iframe = document.createElement('iframe');
    iframe.style.display = 'none';
    document.body.appendChild(iframe);
    try {
      const storage = iframe.contentWindow?.localStorage;
      return storage ? fn(storage) : fallback;
    } finally {
      document.body.removeChild(iframe);
    }
  } catch {
    return fallback;
  }
};
```

Then update setLocalStorage to:
1. Try `window.localStorage` first (existing code)
2. If undefined, fall back to `withIframeStorage(s => s.setItem(key, value), undefined)` (and optionally log a warning so plugin authors can see the fallback is being used)

Same pattern for removeLocalStorage.

Also refactor getLocalStorage and findLocalStorageEntry to use the same helper for consistency. Currently they each have their own copy of the iframe creation/removal code.

For tests, follow the existing iframe fallback test pattern in storage.test.ts (lines 71-106 for getLocalStorage's iframe tests). Mock document.createElement to return a mock iframe with a fake contentWindow.localStorage. Test:
1. setLocalStorage writes via iframe when localStorage is undefined, and the value persists in the mock iframe storage
2. removeLocalStorage removes via iframe when localStorage is undefined

Constraints:
- Do NOT change the public API signatures — setLocalStorage stays `(key: string, value: string): void`, removeLocalStorage stays `(key: string): void`
- Do NOT change getSessionStorage/setSessionStorage/removeSessionStorage — sessionStorage deletion is not a known real-world issue
- The iframe must always be removed in a finally block, even if the storage operation throws
- The functions must never throw — all errors must be caught and either logged or silently ignored
